<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Proposition"
         id="Thm_ProjectionVectorOnLine"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Orthogonal Projection of a Vector on a Line</caption>
   <associate type="Illustration">
      <unit.ref unitId="Illu_ProjectionVectorLine"/>
      <info>
         <para>
            <para.body>An illustration of the effect of the projection process.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <associate type="Explanation">
      <info>
         <info.caption>Explanation of a Computational Expression in the Projection Formula</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Note that the expression</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.display>
            <latex>\dfrac{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{y}} }{ \DotPr{\Vect{y}}{\Vect{y}} }</latex>
         </math.display>
         <para>
            <para.body>is a number. In fact, it is the number by which <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> must be multiplied to give <math>
                  <latex>\pr_{L}(\Vect{x})</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>A Special Case of this Proposition</info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>Note this special case: if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> is parallel to <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>, then <math>
                  <latex>\text{proj}_{L}(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{x}</latex>
               </math>. Therefore, in this case, the projection formula tells us how we need to stretch or shrink <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> to obtain <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>Let <math>
               <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
            </math> be an arbitrary vector of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>, and let <math>
               <latex>L</latex>
            </math> be the line through the origin in the direction of a nonzero vector <math>
               <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
            </math>. Then the orthogonal projection of <math>
               <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
            </math> onto <math>
               <latex>L</latex>
            </math> is the vector
 			</para.body>
         <index.symbol>
            <symbol>
               <math>
                  <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x})</latex>
               </math>
            </symbol>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                     </math> denotes the orthogonal projection of a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> onto the line <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> in the direction of the nonzero vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.symbol>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>orthogonal</term>
            <term>projection of a vector along a line</term>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The projection of a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> onto the line <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> in the direction of the nonzero vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> is the vector</para.body>
               </para>
               <math.display>
                  <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = \dfrac{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{y}} }{ \DotPr{\Vect{y}}{\Vect{y}} } \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math.display>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>projection</term>
            <term>of a vector along a line</term>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>The projection of a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> onto the line <math>
                        <latex>L</latex>
                     </math> in the direction of the nonzero vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> is the vector</para.body>
               </para>
               <math.display>
                  <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = \dfrac{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{y}} }{ \DotPr{\Vect{y}}{\Vect{y}} } \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math.display>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <math.display>
         <latex>\pr_L(\Vect{x}) = \dfrac{ \DotPr{\Vect{x}}{\Vect{y}} }{ \DotPr{\Vect{y}}{\Vect{y}} } \cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
      </math.display>
      <para>
         <para.body>Moreover, <math>
               <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
            </math> is perpendicular to <math>
               <latex>\Vect{x} - \pr_{L}(\Vect{x})</latex>
            </math>.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>We know that the projection vector has the direction of <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>. So 
			<subordinate>
                  <hot>there is a number <math>
                        <latex>t</latex>
                     </math>
                  </hot>
                  <info>
                     <info.caption>Why does such a number exist?</info.caption>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Here we need the assumption that <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y} \neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                           </math>. With this assumption we have, by definition, that a vector <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                           </math> is parallel to <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math> exactly when there is a number <math>
                              <latex>s</latex>
                           </math> with <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z} = s\cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
                           </math>. – In the case at hand, <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z}</latex>
                           </math> is the projection of <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                           </math> onto <math>
                              <latex>L</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </subordinate> with <math>
                  <latex>\text{proj}_L(\Vect{x}) = t\cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>. For a given number <math>
                  <latex>t</latex>
               </math>, set</para.body>
         </para>
         <para align="center">
            <para.body>
               <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{u} := \Vect{x} - t\cdot \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> so that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = t\cdot \Vect{y} + \Vect{u}</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para align="center">
            <para.body>
               <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img xmlns="" src="ims/ProjectionVectorLine_1.gif"/>
               </media>
            </para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Then <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
               </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> if and only if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{u} \bullet \Vect{y} = 0</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para align="center">
            <para.body>
               <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                  <img xmlns="" src="ims/ProjectionVectorLine_2.gif"/>
               </media>
            </para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>We find the number <math>
                  <latex>t</latex>
               </math> for which this happens by dot producting both sides of the equation <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = t\cdot \Vect{y} + \Vect{u}</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>:</para.body>
         </para>
         <table align="center">
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ (t \Vect{y} + \Vect{u}) }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this computational step true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the distributivity law of the dot product.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex> \DotPr{ (t \Vect{y}) }{ \Vect{y} } + \DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this computational step true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the fact that <math>
                                       <latex>\DotPr{ (t\cdot \Vect{y}) }{ \Vect{y} } = t\, ( \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} })</latex>
                                    </math>, and that <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{u}</latex>
                                    </math> is to be perpendicular to <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>t ( \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} }) + 0</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>t</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this computational step true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use again that <math>
                                       <latex>\Vect{y} \neq \Vect{0}</latex>
                                    </math>; so we are allowed to divide by the positive number <math>
                                       <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} } }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </table>
         <para>
            <para.body>It remains to show that <math>
                  <latex>\pr_{L}(\Vect{x})</latex>
               </math> is perpendicular to <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} - \pr_{L}(\Vect{x})</latex>
               </math>; i.e. we need to check that the dot product of the two vectors vanishes. So we compute</para.body>
         </para>
         <table align="center">
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ (\Vect{x} - \pr_{L}(\Vect{x} ) }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \left( \Vect{x} - \dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{  \Vect{y} } }\cdot \Vect{y} \right) }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the distributivity property of the dot product:</para.body>
                              </para>
                              <math.display>
                                 <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ (\Vect{v} + \Vect{w}) } = \DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{v} }\ +\ \DotPr{ \Vect{u} }{ \Vect{w} }</latex>
                              </math.display>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{x} } - \dfrac{ \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } }{ \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} } }\cdot \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we cancel by <math>
                                       <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                                    </math>
                                 </para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{x} } - \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <subordinate>
                           <hot>
                              <math>
                                 <latex>=</latex>
                              </math>
                           </hot>
                           <info>
                              <info.caption>Why is this true?</info.caption>
                              <para>
                                 <para.body>Here we use the commutativity property of the dot product: <math>
                                       <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } = \DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{x} }</latex>
                                    </math>, and we canceled by <math>
                                       <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{y} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                                    </math>.</para.body>
                              </para>
                           </info>
                        </subordinate>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} } - \DotPr{ \Vect{x} }{ \Vect{y} }</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body> </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
               <cell>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>
                     </para.body>
                  </para>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </table>
         <para>
            <para.body>So the two vectors in question are, indeed, perpendicular. – This completes the proof.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
